<img class="" src="http://meetingtomorrow.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/XIAFLEX_DC_LOGO_P.png" alt="" width="168" height="50" /><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #ff6600;"><strong>
INDICATION</strong></span>

<span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;">XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> is indicated for the treatment of adult patients with Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture with a palpable cord.</span>

<span style="font-size: 12px; color: #ff6600;"><strong>IMPORTANT SAFETY INFORMATION FORÂ XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup></strong></span>
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> is contraindicated in patients with a history of hypersensitivity to XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> or to collagenase used in any other therapeutic application or application method</span></span></li>
	<li><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">In the controlled and uncontrolled portions of clinical trials in Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture, flexor tendon ruptures occurred after XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> Injection of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> into collagen-containing structures such as tendons or ligaments of the hand may result in damage to those structures and possible permanent injury such as tendon rupture or ligament damage. Therefore, XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> should be injected only into the collagen cord with a MP or PIP joint contracture, and care should be taken to avoid injecting into tendons, nerves, blood vessels, or other collagen-containing structures of the hand. When injecting a cord affecting a PIP joint of the fifth finger, the needle insertion should not be more than 2 to 3 mm in depth and avoid injecting more than 4 mm distal to the palmar digital crease</span></span></li>
	<li><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Other XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup>-associated serious local adverse reactions in the controlled and uncontrolled portions of the studies included pulley rupture, ligament injury, complex regional pain syndrome (CRPS), sensory abnormality of the hand, and skin laceration (tear). In a historically controlled postmarketing trial, the incidence of skin laceration (22%) was higher for subjects treated with two concurrent injections of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> compared with subjects treated with up to three single injections in the placebo-controlled premarketing trials (9%).Â </span></span><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Cases of skin laceration requiring skin graft after finger extension procedures have been reported post-marketing. Signs or symptoms that may reflect serious injury to the injected finger/hand should be promptly evaluated because surgical intervention may be required.</span></span></li>
	<li><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">In the controlled portions of the clinical trials in Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture, a greater proportion of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup>-treated patients (15%) compared to placebo-treated patients (1%) had mild allergic reactions (pruritus) after up to 3 injections. The incidence of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup>-associated pruritus increased after more XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> injections in patients with Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture</span></span></li>
	<li><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Because XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> contains foreign proteins, severe allergic reactions to XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> can occur. Anaphylaxis was reported in a post-marketing clinical study in one patient who had previous exposure to XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> for the treatment of Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture. Healthcare providers should be prepared to address severe allergic reactions following XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> injections.</span></span></li>
	<li><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">In the XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> trials in Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture, 70% and 38% of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup>-treated patients developed an ecchymosis/contusion or an injection site hemorrhage, respectively. Patients with abnormal coagulation (except for patients taking low-dose aspirin, eg, up to 150 mg per day) were excluded from participating in these studies. Therefore, the efficacy and safety of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> in patients receiving anticoagulant medications (other than low-dose aspirin, eg, up to 150 mg per day) within 7 days prior to XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> administration is not known. In addition, it is recommended to avoid use of XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> in patients with coagulation disorders, including patients receiving concomitant anticoagulants (except for low-dose aspirin)</span></span>Â </span></li>
	<li><span style="font-size: 12px; color: #000000;">In the XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> clinical trials for Dupuytrenâ€™s contracture, the most common adverse reactions reported in â‰¥25% of patients treated with XIAFLEX<sup>Â®</sup> and at an incidence greater than placebo were edema peripheral (eg, swelling of the injected hand), contusion, injection site hemorrhage, injection site reaction, and pain in the injected extremity</span></li>
</ul>
